%PAGE chapter
# SELECT MASTER DEGREE | WORK {{bookmark sm-work-1}}

Note: The characters in this degree are represented as follows:

%TABS 0.7in 1.5in 2.8in
: I._M. : King Solomon : (K._S.) :
: D._M. : Hiram King of Tyre : (H._K._T.) :
: P._C._W. : Hiram Abiff : (H._A.) :
%TABS

Note: The Altar is placed in the Southwest. During the first
   portion of the prologue, the Preparation Room
   represents the Inner Gate; the Sentinel's Room
   represents the Outer Court of the Temple; and the
   Council Room represents the Inner Court of the
   Temple, although it may be pre-arranged as required
   for the Reception (look ahead to Fig. 22), with the
   lights dimmed, as the candidate(s) will not see into it
   until the prologue is complete. {{endnote-ref sm-hall}}

KS: Companions, I am about to confer the Select Master
    Degree upon Companion(s) A, B, C, and D. Are there
    any objections? (_Pause._) Hearing none, I shall proceed.
    Companion Conductor of the Council (_C._C. rises_)
    retire to the preparation room, prepare and conduct the
    candidate(s) to the Outer Court of the Temple.

Note: C._C. first partially opens the door to the Sentinel's
   room, then crosses to the Preparation Room door
   and retires through it, closing it. Candidate(s)
   prepared by wearing the apron as a Master Mason.

CC: (_Conducting candidate towards the Sentinel's room._)
   Companion(s), you now represent Zabud, a particular
   friend of King Solomon. The hour is late, and your
   labors for the day are complete. (_Entering Sentinel's
   room._) Let us rest for a moment, here in the Outer Court
   of the Temple, before returning home. {{endnote-ref zabud}}

Note: C._C. should enter the Sentinel's room first and
   situate the candidate(s) so as not to see inside the
   Council Room. C._C. seats candidate(s) and himself.
   Inside the Council Room, the Three Grand Masters
   and C._G. come to the altar which is in the southwest,
   near the door. The Grand Masters stand on east side,
   facing west, and C._G. stands on the west side, facing
   east. Gong sounds nine times. (See Fig. 17)

KS: Grand Master H._A., how goes the hour?
HA: Nine at night.
KS: It being nine at night, let us resume our labors. As we
   are taught never to enter upon any great or important
   undertaking without first invoking the aid of Deity, let
   us kneel for the benefit of prayer. ||
   {{endnote-ref kneeling-prayer}}

Note: Companions circle about the altar. Those who are
   readily capable of doing so take the front row and
   kneel on right knee. Others stand behind with right
   hand on the shoulder of the Companion before them
   and bow their heads. (See Fig. 18)

KS: O [[smallcaps]]Lord[[/smallcaps]], support us all the day long, until the shadows
   lengthen and the evening comes, the busy world is
   hushed, the fever of life is over, and our work is done.
   Then, in thy mercy, grant us a safe lodging, a holy rest,
   and lasting peace.  Amen. {{endnote-ref sm-work-1-divine-pronouns}}

Note: All arise.
%PAGE figure
Figure 17.

